'''Nagara Shrine''' (ながらじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Nagara, {{ill|lt=Gose|Q847334|qid=Q847334|1=Gose, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}; its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=old ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. It is also called "Hime-no-Miya."

=== Enshrined deity ===
The shrine enshrines one deity<ref name="説明板">Precinct information board.</ref>:
* {{ill|lt=Shitateruhime|Q11307233|qid=Q11307233|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|1=Shitateruhime}} (したてるひめのみこと)

Texts also present other theories: {{ill|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}} or Takateruhime-no-Mikoto{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}. The Kotoshironushi theory derives from '{{ill|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|Q1045362|qid=Q1045362|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}' entry "Yamato Province divine lineage, Nagara no Obito" which states the ancestor as "Ame-no-yae Kotoshironushi." The Takateruhime theory derives from {{ill|lt=Katsuragi Mitoshi Shrine|Q11620955|qid=Q11620955|1=Katsuragi Mitoshi Shrine}} (also popularly called "Nagarahime Shrine") enshrining Takateruhime as associated deity{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}. Another view says the Nagara clan originally enshrined their ancestor deity, but later traditions linking this shrine as a "hime-no-miya" of {{ill|lt=Katsuragi Hitokotonushi Shrine|Q11620885|qid=Q11620885|1=Katsuragi Hitokotonushi Shrine}} or {{ill|lt=Takakamo Shrine|Q11673295|qid=Q11673295|1=Takakamo Shrine}} gave rise to Takateruhime (sister deity of Kotoshironushi) and Shitateruhime (sister deity of {{ill|lt=Ajisukitakahikone|Q506610|qid=Q506610|lt=Ajisukitakahikone-no-Mikoto|1=Ajisukitakahikone}}) theories{{Sfn|長柄神社（神々）|1985年}}.

=== History ===
Founding is unknown{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}. The '{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|qid=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}' mentions "Katsuragi Nagae"; "Nagae" and "Nagara" are said to be synonymous, meaning a long ridge of Mount Katsuragi<ref name="説明板"/>. There is also a theory identifying this place with "Hegumi Nagara Oka-saki" in the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}' pre-enthronement chronicle of {{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|qid=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}}, year Kimi, 2nd month, 20th day{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}{{Sfn|長柄神社（神々）|1985年}} (another theory identifies it with Nagara-chō in {{ill|lt=Tenri|Q502196|qid=Q502196|1=Tenri, Nara}} by context). Near the shrine are known finds including a {{ill|lt=dōtaku|Q2312868|qid=Q2312868|1=Dōtaku}} (Nagara dōtaku), multi-knob fine-line mirror, and a mid-{{ill|lt=5th century|Q8095|qid=Q8095|1=5th century}} chieftain residence site (Nagara site).

Texts also note that the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}' entry for {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenmu|Q335181|qid=Q335181|1=Emperor Tenmu}} 9 ({{ill|lt=680|Q23453|qid=Q23453|1=680}}), 9th month, 9th day says the emperor held mounted archery at "Nagara no Mori," inferred as this shrine grove{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}{{Sfn|長柄神社（神々）|1985年}}.

In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), it is listed in {{ill|lt=Katsuragi District|Q11620858|qid=Q11620858|1=Katsujō district}}, Yamato Province, as "Nagara Shrine, small, hoe and quiver," indicating listing as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} and that hoes and quivers were offered by the court at {{ill|lt=Kinen-sai|Q118906710|qid=Q118906710|1=Kinensai}}{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}.

Later history is unclear, but ridge tags survive back to {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q1324807|qid=Q1324807|1=Shōwa (1312–1317)}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1312|Q5734|qid=Q5734|1=1312}}) of the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|qid=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}} for construction/reconstruction of the honden. Also, a 1418 ({{ill|lt=Ōei|Q1193078|qid=Q1193078|1=Ōei}} 25) "Handa-shō Chūshinbun" in the 'Kasuga Shrine documents' records "Nagara no Miya," identified with this shrine{{SFn|長柄神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|qid=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, it was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}{{Sfn|長柄神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

=== Precinct ===
[[File:Nagara-jinja (Gose) honden.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Honden (Nara Prefecture designated cultural property)}}]]
The honden is ikken-sha {{ill|lt=Kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|qid=Q3193781|1=Kasuga-zukuri}}. Exterior is vermilion-lacquered; the roof was formerly {{ill|lt=hiwadabuki|Q90373477|qid=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}} but is now copper-plate roofed. Zen-style details are seen; though construction date is unknown, it is estimated to date back to the mid-{{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|qid=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. Seventeen ridge tags survive, oldest from 1312; from style they are inferred to correspond to tags of {{ill|lt=Kakitsu|Q1193238|qid=Q1193238|1=Kakitsu}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1441|Q6402|qid=Q6402|1=1441}}) or {{ill|lt=Chōkyō|Q968843|qid=Q968843|1=Chōkyō}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1489|Q6665|qid=Q6665|1=1489}}). This honden is designated Nara Prefecture cultural property{{Sfn|長柄神社（式内社）|1982年}}{{Sfn|奈良県史 8|1998年|pp=893-894}}<ref name="説明板"/>.

